node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Ocean Obsessions on September 04, 2021. May be an image of ocean.

node.text:
Swipe left !!
A pair of pantropical spotted dolphins ride the pressure wave on the nose of a blue whale.
📸 by @scottwilsonimagery

"The mighty and magnificent Blue Whale is the largest animal that has ever lived on this planet. They are gentle giants, filter feeding on plankton and copepods. A century ago they numbered in the hundreds of thousands and were common in oceans around the world. Today there may be as few as 10.000 Blue Whales left due to relentless hunting by humans, ship-strikes from international shipping traffic and ocean plastic- which they ingest while filter feeding. It’s vital we protect the Blue whale and our oceans. Whales are incredibly important for sequestering carbon, their movements while diving from the surface to the depths stimulate the movement of ocean nutrients and ensure healthy populations of phytoplankton- essential for storing carbon from our atmosphere."
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
